00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:36.320
But I thought I'd
remind you, nonetheless,

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:38.870
that we had a last lecture--
the universe was not

00:00:38.870 --> 00:00:41.300
created between then and now.

00:00:41.300 --> 00:00:43.640
And what we talked
about last time

00:00:43.640 --> 00:00:47.850
was the spacetime
geodesic equation,

00:00:47.850 --> 00:00:49.170
which is written this way.

00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:52.090
It's a completely
identical to the equation

00:00:52.090 --> 00:00:56.470
we derived for geodesics
in pure spatial situations.

00:00:56.470 --> 00:00:59.490
The only difference really,
is a difference in notation.

00:00:59.490 --> 00:01:01.390
Instead of using i
and j the tradition

00:01:01.390 --> 00:01:05.890
is to use mu, nu, et cetera
for the spacetime indices which

00:01:05.890 --> 00:01:11.780
are sum from 0 to 3, where
x super 0 is identical to t.

00:01:11.780 --> 00:01:14.970
And in addition, the parameter
which is sometimes called s

00:01:14.970 --> 00:01:17.840
when we're talking about
space, is called tau

00:01:17.840 --> 00:01:19.760
when we're talking
about time because what

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:22.370
the parameter refers
to is the proper time

00:01:22.370 --> 00:01:26.000
along the trajectory of the
object whose geodesic we're

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:28.810
calculating.

00:01:28.810 --> 00:01:31.560
We then introduced the
Schwarzschild metric,

00:01:31.560 --> 00:01:35.350
which we did not
derive, but we claimed

00:01:35.350 --> 00:01:38.190
it describes the metric for
any spherically symmetric mass

00:01:38.190 --> 00:01:40.490
distribution as long
as you're talking

00:01:40.490 --> 00:01:44.910
about the region outside
where the masses are located.

00:01:44.910 --> 00:01:47.290
And here M is the total
mass of the object, which

00:01:47.290 --> 00:01:49.840
is the only thing the
metric really depends on,

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:54.520
G is Newton's constant, and C
is of course the speed of light.

00:01:54.520 --> 00:01:56.350
The metric has an
interesting feature

00:01:56.350 --> 00:01:58.770
that the coefficients
of both the dt

00:01:58.770 --> 00:02:03.750
squared term and to dr squared
term becomes singular either 0

00:02:03.750 --> 00:02:06.770
or infinity, depending on
which one you're looking at,

00:02:06.770 --> 00:02:09.620
a particular value of the
radius called the Schwarzschild

00:02:09.620 --> 00:02:14.380
radius, given by this formula
2 GM divided by c squared.

00:02:14.380 --> 00:02:17.160
The bigger the mass the bigger
the Schwarzschild radius,

00:02:17.160 --> 00:02:19.380
they're proportional
to each other.

00:02:19.380 --> 00:02:21.900
The metric is singular
at those points,

00:02:21.900 --> 00:02:24.630
but I mentioned
but did not prove,

00:02:24.630 --> 00:02:27.250
that that particular
singularity is

00:02:27.250 --> 00:02:30.900
in fact what is referred to
as a coordinate singularity.

00:02:30.900 --> 00:02:33.530
It's a singularity that's
there only because of the way

00:02:33.530 --> 00:02:35.495
the coordinates were chosen.

00:02:35.495 --> 00:02:37.870
So there are other ways of
choosing the coordinates where

00:02:37.870 --> 00:02:40.650
that singularity disappears.

00:02:40.650 --> 00:02:43.209
There's also singularity
at r equals zero,

00:02:43.209 --> 00:02:44.750
and that singularity
is real, there's

00:02:44.750 --> 00:02:46.860
no way to remove
that singularity

00:02:46.860 --> 00:02:48.185
by a change of coordinates.

00:02:51.690 --> 00:02:56.470
However, although r sub s
is not a true singularity,

00:02:56.470 --> 00:02:58.470
it is a horizon.

00:02:58.470 --> 00:03:04.320
And by that we mean that if any
particle or even a light beam

00:03:04.320 --> 00:03:07.720
gets inside the Schwarzschild
radius, it can never get out.

00:03:07.720 --> 00:03:13.225
There's no geodesic which will
take it out of the horizon.

00:03:13.225 --> 00:03:14.950
And it's not even a
matter of geodesics,

00:03:14.950 --> 00:03:17.660
there are no
time-like paths even

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:20.330
if you have a rocket which
would then not follow geodesic.

00:03:20.330 --> 00:03:23.950
There's no way to get out
from inside a black hole.

00:03:23.950 --> 00:03:28.140
We didn't show that, but
that fact is claimed.

00:03:28.140 --> 00:03:32.660
Then we calculated the geodesic
for our radially falling

00:03:32.660 --> 00:03:33.300
object.

00:03:33.300 --> 00:03:35.260
We solve the problem
of an object that

00:03:35.260 --> 00:03:38.360
is released from rest at
some initial value r sub 0,

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:41.590
and just let fall straight
down towards the center

00:03:41.590 --> 00:03:42.580
of the sphere.

00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:47.660
And the the equation
describing the geodesic

00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:51.020
is just a special case
of the general equation

00:03:51.020 --> 00:03:52.680
that we had a few slides ago.

00:03:52.680 --> 00:03:54.990
And we need only look
at the radial component

00:03:54.990 --> 00:03:57.630
if we want to track how the
radius changes with time.

00:03:57.630 --> 00:04:01.270
So there was a free index
mu in the generic form

00:04:01.270 --> 00:04:05.700
of the equation, we're setting
mu equal to the r variable.

00:04:05.700 --> 00:04:08.420
And then the equation
reduces to this form

00:04:08.420 --> 00:04:12.450
and we know what these G sub
t t's and G sub r r's are,

00:04:12.450 --> 00:04:15.060
they come from the equation
for the Schwarzschild metric

00:04:15.060 --> 00:04:16.910
on the previous slide.

00:04:16.910 --> 00:04:18.750
And that equation
can be manipulated

00:04:18.750 --> 00:04:21.125
and eventually it simplifies
to something extraordinarily

00:04:21.125 --> 00:04:22.050
simple.

00:04:22.050 --> 00:04:25.530
It's just the statement that
d squared r d tau squared is

00:04:25.530 --> 00:04:29.920
equal to minus GM over r
squared, which looks exactly

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:32.380
like the Newtonian equation
for something falling

00:04:32.380 --> 00:04:35.107
in a spherically symmetric
gravitational field.

00:04:35.107 --> 00:04:36.690
But it's not really
the same equation,

00:04:36.690 --> 00:04:39.356
it just looks like it's the same
equation, because the variables

00:04:39.356 --> 00:04:41.180
both a different
meanings. r and tau

00:04:41.180 --> 00:04:43.840
both have different meanings
from the r and t that

00:04:43.840 --> 00:04:46.950
would have appeared in
the Newtonian calculation.

00:04:46.950 --> 00:04:49.200
The r variable that
appears here is not really

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:50.707
the distance from the origin.

00:04:50.707 --> 00:04:52.790
If you wanted to know the
distance from the origin

00:04:52.790 --> 00:04:55.160
you'd have to integrate
the metric singular even--

00:04:55.160 --> 00:04:57.600
if not even a well defined
distance to the origin

00:04:57.600 --> 00:05:00.510
because the origin singular.

00:05:00.510 --> 00:05:04.000
And the tau that appears
here is a time variable,

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:07.064
but it's not the time that would
be read on any fixed clock,

00:05:07.064 --> 00:05:08.480
rather it's the
time that would be

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:11.070
read on the wristwatch
of the person falling

00:05:11.070 --> 00:05:14.180
into the spherically symmetric
object, which we might consider

00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:15.000
to be a black hole.

00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:22.250
And we were able to
solve this equation

00:05:22.250 --> 00:05:24.660
by using essentially
conservation of energy

00:05:24.660 --> 00:05:27.261
techniques, or at least what
would be called conservation

00:05:27.261 --> 00:05:29.260
of energy if we were doing
the Newtonian version

00:05:29.260 --> 00:05:31.420
of the problem, which is
the same equation even

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:34.740
though the variables have
a different interpretation.

00:05:34.740 --> 00:05:37.240
So we were able to calculate
not r as a function of tau,

00:05:37.240 --> 00:05:40.570
but at least tau
a function of r.

00:05:40.570 --> 00:05:43.770
And we got that equation,
which is a little complicated,

00:05:43.770 --> 00:05:45.320
but the interesting
thing about it

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:49.960
is that it gives finite answers
for every value of r going

00:05:49.960 --> 00:05:53.020
all the way down
to r equals zero.

00:05:53.020 --> 00:05:55.810
So it means that in a
finite amount of time,

00:05:55.810 --> 00:05:59.770
as seen by the person
falling into the black hole,

00:05:59.770 --> 00:06:02.740
the person would reach r
equals zero, at which point

00:06:02.740 --> 00:06:04.710
he would disappear
into the singularity.

00:06:04.710 --> 00:06:06.780
He'd actually be ripped
apart as he approached

00:06:06.780 --> 00:06:08.950
the singularity
because of tidal forces

00:06:08.950 --> 00:06:12.480
which pull more strongly
on the front part of him

00:06:12.480 --> 00:06:16.360
than on the back part of him,
stretching the object out

00:06:16.360 --> 00:06:19.440
in the radial direction.

00:06:19.440 --> 00:06:23.830
However, curiously,
if one calculates

00:06:23.830 --> 00:06:25.820
what this trajectory
looks like as a function

00:06:25.820 --> 00:06:29.300
of the coordinate time,
t, we did actually

00:06:29.300 --> 00:06:31.240
do that calculation
but we looked

00:06:31.240 --> 00:06:35.230
at how it would
behave in the limit

00:06:35.230 --> 00:06:37.720
as you approached-- as
the particle approached

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:39.010
the Schwarzschild horizon.

00:06:39.010 --> 00:06:41.850
And we discovered it would take
an infinite amount of time,

00:06:41.850 --> 00:06:44.980
as seen from the outside,
for the in falling object

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:47.700
to reach the horizon, let
go through the horizon

00:06:47.700 --> 00:06:49.500
and get to r equals zero.

00:06:49.500 --> 00:06:52.280
So from the outside, it
looks like the object never

00:06:52.280 --> 00:06:54.210
actually falls into
the black hole,

00:06:54.210 --> 00:06:57.220
but just gets closer and closer
and closer as t approaches

00:06:57.220 --> 00:06:58.240
infinity.

00:06:58.240 --> 00:07:01.830
So it's an example of a very
highly distorted spacetime,

00:07:01.830 --> 00:07:04.400
where you can see very
different pictures depending

00:07:04.400 --> 00:07:08.250
on which observer you're
trying to describe

00:07:08.250 --> 00:07:09.350
the observations of.

